# Commit and push after every change

Whenever you modify project code (features, fixes, refactors, copy, config that belongs in the repo):

1. Run `git status` in the repo root and stage only relevant files (never commit secrets, `.env`, `.env.local`, or unrelated local files).
2. Commit with a clear message describing what changed.
3. Push to GitHub: `git push origin <current-branch>` (usually `main`).

Do not finish a coding task without pushing, unless `git push` fails — then report the error and confirm what was committed locally.

If push fails (auth, network), report the error and what was committed locally. Do not assume deployment (e.g. Vercel) ran unless the user confirms it.
